top_ten_names <- seattle_pets %>%
  group_by(animals_name) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  head(10)

top_ten_primary_breed <- seattle_pets %>%
  group_by(primary_breed) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  head(10)

top_ten_secondary_breed <- seattle_pets %>%
  group_by(secondary_breed) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  head(10)

top_ten_zip_code <- seattle_pets %>%
  group_by(zip_code) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(count)) %>%
  head(10)

Something isnt working but the choropleths package does have exactly what I needed: a way to match zipcodes to a lat-long pair. So, first I need to add that information to my dataset.

sp_geo <- seattle_pets %>% 
  left_join(select(zip.map, long, lat, region), by = c("zip_code" = "region")) %>%
  group_by(license_issue_date, license_number, animals_name, species, primary_breed, secondary_breed, zip_code) %>% 
  summarize(long = mean(long, na.rm = TRUE), lat = mean(lat,na.rm = TRUE))

And now we make a map

seattle <- c(lon = mean(sp_geo$long, na.rm = TRUE), lat = mean(sp_geo$lat, na.rm = TRUE))
seattle_map <- get_map(seattle, zoom = 12)
## Source : https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/staticmap?center=47.630839,-122.335049&zoom=12&size=640x640&scale=2&maptype=terrain&language=en-EN&key=xxx-NN0kD3fMANP5ReB1Mc_O9b5SMs0jk
sp_for_map <- sp_geo %>%
  group_by(long, lat) %>% 
  summarise(count = n())

ggmap(seattle_map) +
  geom_point(aes(long, lat, size = count), data = sp_for_map)
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

sp_for_name_map <- sp_geo %>%
  group_by(long, lat) %>% 
  summarise(top_name = mode(animals_name), count = n()) 

ggmap(seattle_map) +
  geom_text(aes(long, lat, label = top_name, size = count), data = sp_for_name_map) +
  theme(legend.position="none")
## Warning: Removed 70 rows containing missing values (geom_text).
